Multiple inheritance and the method resolution order.

Python supports multiple inheritance. When several base classes define the same method, lookup follows the method resolution order — python's c-three linearization, a deterministic ordering of all ancestor classes.

Picture class a, class b of a, class c of a, class d of b and c. D dot greet returns b arrow c arrow a. The method resolution order of d is bracket d, b, c, a, object bracket. Python finds b's implementation first. B's greet calls super dot greet — which in the resolution order goes to c's greet. C's greet calls super dot greet — which goes to a's greet.

The rule for the diamond. Every class appears exactly once, in an order that respects each parent's ordering and puts subclasses before their parents. You inspect the order with c-l-s dot dunder-m-r-o or c-l-s dot m-r-o.

In code, picture the diamond. A, b of a, c of a, d of b and c. D dot dunder-m-r-o shows the linearization. D dot greet returns the chained b-arrow-c-arrow-a. The method resolution order is computed once, deterministically, at class creation time.
